  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 홍범(洪範) : '
    value: 《서경(書經)》의 편 이름. 은(殷)의 기자(箕子)가 주무왕(周武王)에게 정치에 대한 기본 원칙을 제시하였다고 전하는 것.
  - key: '[주-D002] 자공(子貢)이 …… 주었다 : '
    value: 자공(子貢)이 공자에게 정치하는 방법을 묻자, 공자는, “식량을 풍족하게 하고, 국방력을 충족하게 하며, 백성에게 신의를 보여야 한다.”고 일렀다. 《논어 안연(論語顔淵)》
english:
  title: On Begging for Food
  author: Jeong Do-jeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The matter of sustenance is grave indeed for humankind. We cannot go a single day without food, nor can we live a single day by merely scrounging for it. Without food, we damage our very life; by scrounging, we corrupt our righteousness. In the Eight Policies of the Hong Fan, food and goods come first. Among the Five Teachings that honor the people, sustenance holds the foremost place. When Zilu asked about governance, Confucius instructed him to ensure the people's food was sufficient. Thus did the ancient sages understand that the welfare of the people cannot endure a single day without food. They taught cultivation and harvest, established systems of tribute and tax, provisioned the military and state, sustained the rites and received guests, and provided for the widowed, orphaned, aged, and young, so that none suffered want or hunger. The sage's concern for the people reached far and wide. Therefore, above, the emperor and the dukes and ministers governed and sustained themselves through the people; below, the farmers, artisans, and merchants toiled diligently and sustained themselves through labor; and in between, the scholars practiced filial piety at home and respect abroad, guarded the Way of ancient kings, and waited to transmit learning to posterity, thus sustaining themselves. The ancient sages knew well that we cannot live by scrounging even for a day. From top to bottom, each held their station, receiving the nourishment of Heaven. Their method of protecting the people was perfect indeed. Those who stand outside this order are wicked people, deserving of the king's law without mercy or pardon.

    The Vajracchedika Sutra says: "At that time the World-Honored One, at mealtime, donned his robes, took his bowl, and entered the city of Sravasti to beg for food within the city."

    Now this Shakyamuni, holding that the household life of men and women is wrong, judging that men plowing and women weaving is unrighteous, stepping outside the bonds of human relations and abandoning the work of cultivation, severing the very root of livelihood—he wishes to transform the world with his doctrine! If his way were truly followed, there would be no people left in the world. How then could there be anyone to give alms? If his way were truly followed, there would be no food left in the world. How then could there be food to beg?

    Shakyamuni was the son of a king of the Western Regions. Deeming his father's throne unrighteous, he refused to occupy it—he was no ruler of people. Deeming men plowing and women weaving unrighteous, he abandoned these labors—where then is his industry? He rejected the bonds of father and son, ruler and subject, husband and wife—he does not preserve the Way of the ancient kings. Thus, even if he ate but a single grain of rice a day, it would all be base scavenging. If his way were truly followed, surely one would have to become as a worm, eating nothing at all. Why then does he beg for food? Moreover, is it that when sustenance comes from one's own labor it becomes unrighteous, yet when begged it becomes righteous? The words of the Buddha contain neither righteousness nor reason. Open the text and such contradictions appear at once. Therefore I write this refutation.
  footnotes:
    - The Hong Fan (Eight Policies) is a chapter of the Book of History attributed to Ji Zi, legendary counselor of the Shang dynasty, who is said to have presented these fundamental principles of governance to King Wu of Zhou.
    - Zilu's question about governance is recorded in the Analects (Yan Yuan 12:7), where Confucius responded that the ruler must ensure sufficient food, adequate defense, and the people's trust.
    - The Vajracchedika Sutra, or Diamond Sutra, is one of the most important Mahayana Buddhist texts, describing Buddha's daily practices and teachings.
